// TEST: exec_bounded_dispatch
// EXPECT: output "hi_beats_lo=yes"
// EXPECT: targets js, ts, python, rust, go
//
// Generic-bounded dispatch (codegen-completeness P2, item 4). A generic
// function `outranks[T: Ranked](a, b)` calls `a.beats(b)` on a value whose type
// is the bounded type variable `T`. The checker resolves `beats` through the
// `Ranked` trait bound, but `recv_kind_tag` returned `None` for a
// `Type::TypeVar` receiver, so codegen got no hint that `a.beats(b)` dispatches
// through a trait.
//
// The fix stamps a new `recv_kind = "TraitBound:Ranked"` annotation at the
// bounded-TypeVar method-resolution path in the checker. Per backend:
//   * TS emits `<T extends Ranked>` (the bound is preserved in the signature)
//     and — via item 2 — the trait-self typing that makes `a.beats(a, b)`
//     callable on `T`.
//   * Go emits a `[T Ranked]` constraint, the method-name casing `a.Beats(b)`,
//     and `Self` -> `T` in the interface signature.
//   * Python emits a plain `a.beats(b)`.
//   * js and rust already worked.
//
// `outranks` is the bounded generic: it dispatches `a.beats(b)` through the
// `Ranked` bound and returns the boolean. The fixture returns a value *derived*
// from the dispatched call (a String), rather than returning one of the two
// operands — Bock's value semantics permit reusing an operand after the call,
// but a generic Rust function returning a moved-and-reused `T` is a separate
// (pre-existing) Rust ownership-model gap, orthogonal to bounded dispatch. See
// the OPEN note in the session PR.
//
// `main` is intentionally NOT `public` (see hello_world.bock for the Go
// entry-point rationale).
module main

trait Ranked {
  fn beats(self, other: Self) -> Bool
}

record Card {
  rank: Int
}

impl Ranked for Card {
  public fn beats(self, other: Card) -> Bool {
    self.rank > other.rank
  }
}

fn outranks[T: Ranked](a: T, b: T) -> Bool {
  a.beats(b)
}

fn yesno(b: Bool) -> String {
  if (b) {
    return "yes"
  }
  return "no"
}

fn main() -> Void {
  let lo: Card = Card { rank: 1 }
  let hi: Card = Card { rank: 2 }
  println("hi_beats_lo=${yesno(outranks(hi, lo))}")
}
